('chunk_ae3dfc1d7a5f8252af','file_2567f8311bd711b854','digital-design.md','Surveys, Data Collection and Data Analysis','**Definition:** Gathering numerical or descriptive data from users (often via a survey/form) and making sense of it.

**How to do it:**
1. Write clear, unbiased questions (avoid leading questions).
2. Use a mix of closed (multiple-choice, rating) and open questions.
3. Collect responses (Google Forms is ideal — it charts results automatically).
4. **Analyse:** summarise with charts, find the most common answers, and state what the data *means* for your design.

**Worked mini-example (Robotics):** Survey question: *"How confident are you using technology at home? (1–5)"* Result: 70% answered 1–2. **Analysis:** most users are low-confidence, so the Maker Bot must have very simple controls and clear instructions.

**Why it matters:** Data turns opinions into evidence. A design decision backed by data is defensible.

**Common misconception:** *"Showing the chart is the analysis."* Correction: a chart is data *display*. **Analysis** explains what the numbers tell you and how they change your design.

**Command-term question:** **Analyse** your survey results and **explain** one design decision they support.','{"surveys":1,"data":7,"collection":1,"and":7,"analysis":4,"definition":1,"gathering":1,"numerical":1,"descriptive":1,"from":1,"users":2,"often":1,"via":1,"survey":3,"form":1,"making":1,"sense":1,"how":3,"write":1,"clear":2,"unbiased":1,"questions":3,"avoid":1,"leading":1,"use":1,"mix":1,"closed":1,"multiple":1,"choice":1,"rating":1,"open":1,"collect":1,"responses":1,"google":1,"forms":1,"ideal":1,"charts":2,"results":2,"automatically":1,"analyse":2,"summarise":1,"with":1,"find":1,"the":6,"most":2,"common":2,"answers":1,"state":1,"what":2,"means":1,"for":1,"your":3,"design":4,"worked":1,"mini":1,"example":1,"robotics":1,"question":2,"confident":1,"are":2,"you":2,"using":1,"technology":1,"home":1,"result":1,"answered":1,"low":1,"confidence":1,"maker":1,"bot":1,"must":1,"have":1,"very":1,"simple":1,"controls":1,"instructions":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"turns":1,"opinions":1,"into":1,"evidence":1,"decision":2,"backed":1,"defensible":1,"misconception":1,"showing":1,"chart":2,"correction":1,"display":1,"explains":1,"numbers":1,"tell":1,"they":2,"change":1,"command":1,"term":1,"explain":1,"one":1,"support":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_e7ba3163d4dcc3cb0f','file_2567f8311bd711b854','digital-design.md','Bibliography and Citation','**Definition:** A list of every source used, formatted so others can find it. Citing gives credit and avoids plagiarism.

**How to do it (checklist):**
1. Record author, title, website/publisher, date, and URL as you research.
2. List sources alphabetically.
3. Use a consistent style (MLA is common in MYP).
4. Cite images and videos too, not just text.

**Worked mini-example:** *Smith, J. "Designing Games for Young Children." GameDesignHub, 2024, www.gamedesignhub.com/kids.* 

**Why it matters:** Academic honesty is an IB core value. Uncited work is plagiarism even if unintentional.

**Common misconception:** *"I put it in my own words, so I don''t need to cite it."* Correction: **ideas and facts** need citing even when reworded — only the wording is yours, not the information.

**Command-term question:** **List** three sources you used in correct bibliographic format.','{"2024":1,"bibliography":1,"and":5,"citation":1,"definition":1,"list":3,"every":1,"source":1,"used":2,"formatted":1,"others":1,"can":1,"find":1,"citing":2,"gives":1,"credit":1,"avoids":1,"plagiarism":2,"how":1,"checklist":1,"record":1,"author":1,"title":1,"website":1,"publisher":1,"date":1,"url":1,"you":2,"research":1,"sources":2,"alphabetically":1,"use":1,"consistent":1,"style":1,"mla":1,"common":2,"myp":1,"cite":2,"images":1,"videos":1,"too":1,"not":2,"just":1,"text":1,"worked":1,"mini":1,"example":1,"smith":1,"designing":1,"games":1,"for":1,"young":1,"children":1,"gamedesignhub":2,"www":1,"com":1,"kids":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"academic":1,"honesty":1,"core":1,"value":1,"uncited":1,"work":1,"even":2,"unintentional":1,"misconception":1,"put":1,"own":1,"words":1,"don":1,"need":2,"correction":1,"ideas":1,"facts":1,"when":1,"reworded":1,"only":1,"the":2,"wording":1,"yours":1,"information":1,"command":1,"term":1,"question":1,"three":1,"correct":1,"bibliographic":1,"format":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_aa07b59d376f2e1695','file_2567f8311bd711b854','digital-design.md','Product Analysis','**Definition:** Studying existing products similar to your intended solution to learn what works and what does not.

**How to do it:**
1. Choose 2–3 existing products related to your problem.
2. Examine function, form, materials, cost, ergonomics, audience.
3. Note strengths and weaknesses of each.
4. Draw conclusions that inform your own design.

**Worked mini-example (Toy/Game):** Analysing *Snakes and Ladders* (simple, luck-based, no skill) vs *Uno* (needs colour/number recognition) reveals that a game for 5–7 year-olds should use bright colours, simple rules and short play time.

**Why it matters:** You rarely design from zero. Existing products are free lessons in what users already accept.

**Common misconception:** *"Product analysis means describing the product."* Correction: description is not analysis — you must **judge** what is good/bad and say why it matters for *your* design.

**Command-term question:** **Analyse** one existing product and **explain** what you will borrow or avoid.','{"product":4,"analysis":3,"definition":1,"studying":1,"existing":4,"products":3,"similar":1,"your":4,"intended":1,"solution":1,"learn":1,"what":5,"works":1,"and":6,"does":1,"not":2,"how":1,"choose":1,"related":1,"problem":1,"examine":1,"function":1,"form":1,"materials":1,"cost":1,"ergonomics":1,"audience":1,"note":1,"strengths":1,"weaknesses":1,"each":1,"draw":1,"conclusions":1,"that":2,"inform":1,"own":1,"design":3,"worked":1,"mini":1,"example":1,"toy":1,"game":2,"analysing":1,"snakes":1,"ladders":1,"simple":2,"luck":1,"based":1,"skill":1,"uno":1,"needs":1,"colour":1,"number":1,"recognition":1,"reveals":1,"for":2,"year":1,"olds":1,"should":1,"use":1,"bright":1,"colours":1,"rules":1,"short":1,"play":1,"time":1,"why":2,"matters":2,"you":3,"rarely":1,"from":1,"zero":1,"are":1,"free":1,"lessons":1,"users":1,"already":1,"accept":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"means":1,"describing":1,"the":1,"correction":1,"description":1,"must":1,"judge":1,"good":1,"bad":1,"say":1,"command":1,"term":1,"question":1,"analyse":1,"one":1,"explain":1,"will":1,"borrow":1,"avoid":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_4a21bee1f2ed39fdd0','file_2567f8311bd711b854','digital-design.md','SWOT Analysis','**Definition:** A structured tool for analysing a product using four lenses: **S**trengths, **W**eaknesses, **O**pportunities, **T**hreats. Strengths/Weaknesses are *internal* (about the product itself); Opportunities/Threats are *external* (about the market/context).

**SWOT template:**

| | Helpful | Harmful |
|--------|---------|---------|
| **Internal (the product)** | **Strengths** — what it does well | **Weaknesses** — what it lacks |
| **External (the world)** | **Opportunities** — trends/gaps to exploit | **Threats** — competitors, risks |

**How to do it:**
1. Pick a product (usually an existing one).
2. Fill each quadrant with specific points.
3. Use SWOT of several products to **compare** and find a gap for your design.

**Worked mini-example (Robotics — analysing an existing plant-watering gadget):**
- **S:** Waters automatically on a timer.
- **W:** No sensor — waters even when soil is wet.
- **O:** Users increasingly want "smart" eco-friendly gadgets.
- **T:** Cheaper competitor products already exist.
Conclusion: our Maker Bot should add a **moisture sensor** (fixing the weakness and seizing the opportunity).

**Why it matters:** SWOT forces you to look beyond the product itself to the market and risks — the same thinking real companies use.

**Common misconception:** *"SWOT is just a list of features."* Correction: SWOT separates *internal vs external* and *helpful vs harmful*. Opportunities and Threats are about the **outside world**, not the product''s parts.

**Command-term question:** **Construct** a SWOT analysis of an existing product related to your problem.','{"swot":7,"analysis":2,"definition":1,"structured":1,"tool":1,"for":2,"analysing":2,"product":7,"using":1,"four":1,"lenses":1,"trengths":1,"eaknesses":1,"pportunities":1,"hreats":1,"strengths":2,"weaknesses":2,"are":3,"internal":3,"about":3,"the":11,"itself":2,"opportunities":3,"threats":3,"external":3,"market":2,"context":1,"template":1,"helpful":2,"harmful":2,"what":2,"does":1,"well":1,"lacks":1,"world":2,"trends":1,"gaps":1,"exploit":1,"competitors":1,"risks":2,"how":1,"pick":1,"usually":1,"existing":3,"one":1,"fill":1,"each":1,"quadrant":1,"with":1,"specific":1,"points":1,"use":2,"several":1,"products":2,"compare":1,"and":5,"find":1,"gap":1,"your":2,"design":1,"worked":1,"mini":1,"example":1,"robotics":1,"plant":1,"watering":1,"gadget":1,"waters":2,"automatically":1,"timer":1,"sensor":2,"even":1,"when":1,"soil":1,"wet":1,"users":1,"increasingly":1,"want":1,"smart":1,"eco":1,"friendly":1,"gadgets":1,"cheaper":1,"competitor":1,"already":1,"exist":1,"conclusion":1,"our":1,"maker":1,"bot":1,"should":1,"add":1,"moisture":1,"fixing":1,"weakness":1,"seizing":1,"opportunity":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"forces":1,"you":1,"look":1,"beyond":1,"same":1,"thinking":1,"real":1,"companies":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"just":1,"list":1,"features":1,"correction":1,"separates":1,"outside":1,"not":1,"parts":1,"command":1,"term":1,"question":1,"construct":1,"related":1,"problem":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_3727c01c8311e13414','file_2567f8311bd711b854','digital-design.md','Comparing Products with SWOT & Summarising Research','**Definition:** Using SWOT across multiple products to compare them, then summarising all research to define the solution.

**How to do it:**
1. SWOT two or three competitor products.
2. Compare quadrants side by side — where do they all fall short?
3. Write a research summary: *"Based on my primary and secondary research and product analysis, the solution should…"*
4. This summary becomes the bridge into Criterion B.

**Worked mini-example:** After comparing three toys, all lack replay value. Summary: *"My game must remain fun over many plays, so it will include variable outcomes."*

**Why it matters:** The summary links evidence to the design brief, proving your solution is research-driven, not guesswork.

**Common misconception:** *"The summary is a recap of everything I did."* Correction: it is a **focused conclusion** stating what the solution needs, drawn from the evidence.

---','{"comparing":2,"products":3,"with":1,"swot":3,"summarising":2,"research":5,"definition":1,"using":1,"across":1,"multiple":1,"compare":2,"them":1,"then":1,"all":3,"define":1,"the":8,"solution":4,"how":1,"two":1,"three":2,"competitor":1,"quadrants":1,"side":2,"where":1,"they":1,"fall":1,"short":1,"write":1,"summary":5,"based":1,"primary":1,"and":2,"secondary":1,"product":1,"analysis":1,"should":1,"this":1,"becomes":1,"bridge":1,"into":1,"criterion":1,"worked":1,"mini":1,"example":1,"after":1,"toys":1,"lack":1,"replay":1,"value":1,"game":1,"must":1,"remain":1,"fun":1,"over":1,"many":1,"plays":1,"will":1,"include":1,"variable":1,"outcomes":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"links":1,"evidence":2,"design":1,"brief":1,"proving":1,"your":1,"driven":1,"not":1,"guesswork":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"recap":1,"everything":1,"did":1,"correction":1,"focused":1,"conclusion":1,"stating":1,"what":1,"needs":1,"drawn":1,"from":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_d093844af4bf6f6580','file_2567f8311bd711b854','digital-design.md','CRITERION B — Developing Ideas','Criterion B turns understanding into **plans and designs**. Students set success criteria, generate and compare design ideas, and map the product''s logic with a flowchart.','{"criterion":2,"developing":1,"ideas":2,"turns":1,"understanding":1,"into":1,"plans":1,"and":3,"designs":1,"students":1,"set":1,"success":1,"criteria":1,"generate":1,"compare":1,"design":1,"map":1,"the":1,"product":1,"logic":1,"with":1,"flowchart":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_d7af4b1fcab07a48f0','file_2567f8311bd711b854','digital-design.md','Success Criteria (Design Specification)','**Definition:** A list of clear, measurable statements that a successful solution **must** meet. Together they form the **design specification**. They are the "test list" you will use in Criterion D.

**How to do it (checklist):**
1. Write 5–8 criteria drawn from your research.
2. Make each **specific and testable** (measurable or clearly checkable).
3. Cover function, audience needs, form, safety, resources.
4. Phrase as "The solution must…".

**Worked mini-example (Toy/Game):**
- The game must be playable by 2–4 children aged 5–7.
- The game must last no longer than 15 minutes.
- The rules must fit on one card and use pictures.
- The game must use only safe, non-toxic, non-choking materials.

**Why it matters:** Success criteria connect A → B → D. You design *to* them (B) and test *against* them (D).

**Common misconception:** *"Success criteria = a list of features."* Correction: criteria are **measurable standards** ("must last under 15 minutes"), not just parts ("has cards"). A feature answers *what*; a criterion answers *how well / how much*, so it can be tested pass/fail.

**Command-term question:** **List** five success criteria and **explain** how each is measurable.','{"success":4,"criteria":6,"design":3,"specification":2,"definition":1,"list":4,"clear":1,"measurable":4,"statements":1,"that":1,"successful":1,"solution":2,"must":7,"meet":1,"together":1,"they":2,"form":2,"the":7,"are":2,"test":2,"you":2,"will":1,"use":3,"criterion":2,"how":4,"checklist":1,"write":1,"drawn":1,"from":1,"your":1,"research":1,"make":1,"each":2,"specific":1,"and":4,"testable":1,"clearly":1,"checkable":1,"cover":1,"function":1,"audience":1,"needs":1,"safety":1,"resources":1,"phrase":1,"worked":1,"mini":1,"example":1,"toy":1,"game":4,"playable":1,"children":1,"aged":1,"last":2,"longer":1,"than":1,"minutes":2,"rules":1,"fit":1,"one":1,"card":1,"pictures":1,"only":1,"safe":1,"non":2,"toxic":1,"choking":1,"materials":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"connect":1,"them":2,"against":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"features":1,"correction":1,"standards":1,"under":1,"not":1,"just":1,"parts":1,"has":1,"cards":1,"feature":1,"answers":2,"what":1,"well":1,"much":1,"can":1,"tested":1,"pass":1,"fail":1,"command":1,"term":1,"question":1,"five":1,"explain":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_c88bf6d8fb2287aee4','file_2567f8311bd711b854','digital-design.md','Design Diagrams and Annotation','**Definition:** Visual drawings of possible solutions, **annotated** (labelled) to explain each part, made in tools such as **draw.io** or **Canva**.

**How to do it:**
1. Sketch **at least two or three** different design ideas.
2. Label every important part (annotation) — material, size, function, colour.
3. Keep ideas genuinely different so there is a real choice.

**Worked mini-example (Robotics):** Two annotated draw.io diagrams of the Maker Bot — Design 1 with wheels + moisture sensor; Design 2 with a fixed base + timer. Annotations note the sensor position, battery, and controller.

**Why it matters:** Diagrams make ideas visible and communicable before you commit resources to building.

**Common misconception:** *"One design idea is enough."* Correction: MYP Design requires **multiple** ideas so you can *compare and justify* a choice.

**Command-term question:** **Present** two annotated design ideas for your solution.','{"design":7,"diagrams":3,"and":4,"annotation":2,"definition":1,"visual":1,"drawings":1,"possible":1,"solutions":1,"annotated":3,"labelled":1,"explain":1,"each":1,"part":2,"made":1,"tools":1,"such":1,"draw":2,"canva":1,"how":1,"sketch":1,"least":1,"two":3,"three":1,"different":2,"ideas":5,"label":1,"every":1,"important":1,"material":1,"size":1,"function":1,"colour":1,"keep":1,"genuinely":1,"there":1,"real":1,"choice":2,"worked":1,"mini":1,"example":1,"robotics":1,"the":2,"maker":1,"bot":1,"with":2,"wheels":1,"moisture":1,"sensor":2,"fixed":1,"base":1,"timer":1,"annotations":1,"note":1,"position":1,"battery":1,"controller":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"make":1,"visible":1,"communicable":1,"before":1,"you":2,"commit":1,"resources":1,"building":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"one":1,"idea":1,"enough":1,"correction":1,"myp":1,"requires":1,"multiple":1,"can":1,"compare":1,"justify":1,"command":1,"term":1,"question":1,"present":1,"for":1,"your":1,"solution":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_5e81cfebc42d3ab404','file_2567f8311bd711b854','digital-design.md','Analysing and Selecting the Best Design','**Definition:** Comparing your design ideas against the success criteria to justify which one to build.

**How to do it:**
1. Make a table: designs as columns, success criteria as rows.
2. Mark how well each design meets each criterion.
3. Choose the best-fitting design and **explain why** with reference to the criteria.

**Worked mini-example:** Design 1 (with sensor) meets the "saves water / eco-friendly" criterion; Design 2 does not. Selected Design 1 because it satisfies more success criteria, especially sustainability.

**Why it matters:** Justified selection shows the choice is evidence-based, not personal preference.

**Common misconception:** *"I pick the one I like best."* Correction: selection must be **justified against the success criteria**, not taste.','{"analysing":1,"and":2,"selecting":1,"the":8,"best":3,"design":7,"definition":1,"comparing":1,"your":1,"ideas":1,"against":2,"success":4,"criteria":5,"justify":1,"which":1,"one":2,"build":1,"how":2,"make":1,"table":1,"designs":1,"columns":1,"rows":1,"mark":1,"well":1,"each":2,"meets":2,"criterion":2,"choose":1,"fitting":1,"explain":1,"why":2,"with":2,"reference":1,"worked":1,"mini":1,"example":1,"sensor":1,"saves":1,"water":1,"eco":1,"friendly":1,"does":1,"not":3,"selected":1,"because":1,"satisfies":1,"more":1,"especially":1,"sustainability":1,"matters":1,"justified":2,"selection":2,"shows":1,"choice":1,"evidence":1,"based":1,"personal":1,"preference":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"pick":1,"like":1,"correction":1,"must":1,"taste":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_abf4c593558850e29e','file_2567f8311bd711b854','digital-design.md','Flowcharts','**Definition:** A diagram that shows the **step-by-step logic** of how the product (or a user''s interaction, or a program) works, using standard symbols.

**Flowchart symbols:**

| Symbol shape | Name | Meaning |
|--------------|------|---------|
| Rounded rectangle / oval | Terminator | Start or End |
| Parallelogram | Input/Output | Get input or show output |
| Rectangle | Process | An action or step |
| Diamond | Decision | A yes/no question that branches |
| Arrow | Flow line | Direction / order of steps |

**How to do it:**
1. Start with a **Start** terminator.
2. Add processes and inputs/outputs in order.
3. Use a diamond wherever the product must *decide* (branch).
4. End with a **Stop** terminator. Follow arrows top-to-bottom.

**Worked mini-example (Robotics — watering logic):**
Start → Read soil moisture (input) → *Is soil dry?* (decision) → if **Yes**: Turn on pump (process) → Wait 5 s → Stop pump; if **No**: do nothing → End.

**Why it matters:** Flowcharts force logical thinking and reveal gaps before building. They are the bridge between an idea and an algorithm.

**Common misconception:** *"A flowchart is just a list of steps in boxes."* Correction: a true flowchart shows **decisions and branches** (diamonds), not only a straight sequence.

**Command-term question:** **Design** a flowchart showing how your solution works, using correct symbols.

---','{"flowcharts":2,"definition":1,"diagram":1,"that":2,"shows":2,"the":4,"step":3,"logic":2,"how":3,"product":2,"user":1,"interaction":1,"program":1,"works":2,"using":2,"standard":1,"symbols":3,"flowchart":4,"symbol":1,"shape":1,"name":1,"meaning":1,"rounded":1,"rectangle":2,"oval":1,"terminator":3,"start":4,"end":3,"parallelogram":1,"input":3,"output":2,"get":1,"show":1,"process":2,"action":1,"diamond":2,"decision":2,"yes":2,"question":2,"branches":2,"arrow":1,"flow":1,"line":1,"direction":1,"order":2,"steps":2,"with":2,"add":1,"processes":1,"and":4,"inputs":1,"outputs":1,"use":1,"wherever":1,"must":1,"decide":1,"branch":1,"stop":2,"follow":1,"arrows":1,"top":1,"bottom":1,"worked":1,"mini":1,"example":1,"robotics":1,"watering":1,"read":1,"soil":2,"moisture":1,"dry":1,"turn":1,"pump":2,"wait":1,"nothing":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"force":1,"logical":1,"thinking":1,"reveal":1,"gaps":1,"before":1,"building":1,"they":1,"are":1,"bridge":1,"between":1,"idea":1,"algorithm":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"just":1,"list":1,"boxes":1,"correction":1,"true":1,"decisions":1,"diamonds":1,"not":1,"only":1,"straight":1,"sequence":1,"command":1,"term":1,"design":1,"showing":1,"your":1,"solution":1,"correct":1}'::jsonb),
